To help ensure that any serious chemical releases do not occur, CSS maintains a release prevention program which is focused on protecting the public and plant employees from the hazards associated with an accident or release involving ammonia.  This multifaceted program includes the use of:

Ammmonia gas detection and alarms to rapidly alert operators to any problems;

Process instrumentation and interlocks which will shutdown the system and isolate ammonia supplies to the plant if process conditions (such as flow, temperature, and pressure) are not within their appropriate safe operating ranges;

Process safety information which documents the safe design of the process system;

Process hazards analysis to evaluate the chemical and process hazards and make recommendations for safety improvements;

Written operating procedures to ensure the system is operated safely;

Maintenance, inspection, and testing of system components to ensure that they are safe for continued use;

Safe work practices to ensure that employees working on and around the processes are aware of the hazards, can perform their job duties safely, and know the actions to be taken in an emergency;

Incident Investigation procedure to investigate accidents and near-misses to determine root causes and make needed safety improvements;

Training on all aspects of the program, operations, maintenance, chemical hazards, emergency response, and related aspects to ensure employees are continually aware of what is required to operate the system safely; and

Periodic compliance audits to ensure that the management system and prevention programs are working as they should.

FIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY

Cliffside has not had any releases that resulted in injuries or property damages.

